    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-07-12_page01.jpg"/>
                    <opener> <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Rutland-Square-45_IE">Rutland Square 45</placeName>
                    <dateline> Tuesday 12<hi rend="superscript">h</hi> 1842
                        <note> 60 </note>
                        <date when="1842-07-12">July 12, 1842</date>
                        <note> July </note></dateline> </opener>
                  
                   <p> 
                       How shocked you must have<lb/>
                       been my dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> by<lb/>
                       the death of our friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FostJ1"><choice>
                       <orig>Les-<lb/>
                       lie</orig>
                       <reg>Leslie</reg>
                       </choice>
                       Foster</persName> - You heard it from<lb/>
                       the newspapers I suppose<lb/>
                       I heard it from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">Charles Fox</persName><lb/>
                       at the moment of my arrival<lb/>
                       here. I never was more <choice> 
                       <orig>sur<lb/>
                       prised</orig>
                       <reg>surprised</reg>
                       </choice>
                       and shocked ! There<lb/>
                       is no mention in the papers<lb/>
                       of his son except that he went<lb/>
                       up to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE">Dublin</placeName> next day --! Poor<lb/>
                       young man He really was<lb/>
                       fond of his father - It must have<lb/>
                       been dreadful for him - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">Charles</persName><lb/>
                       tells me that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#VeseL1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Foster</persName> could<lb/>
                       not believe that her husband was<lb/>
                        really dead - <del>you</del> She had always <choice> 
                       <orig>ima<lb/>
                       gined</orig>
                       <reg>imagined</reg>
                       </choice>
                       that her son who was drowned<lb/>
                       might have been recovered if more<lb/>
                       pains had been taken and upon this<lb/>
                       recollection she persisted in believing<lb/>
                       that her husband might be recovered<lb/>
                       and she wanted to <del>send or</del> to take <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarsH1" cert="high">Marsh</persName><lb/>
                       down to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Cavan_IE">Cavan</placeName> immediately But he<lb/>
                       would not go: he said here are two <choice> 
                       <orig>phy<lb/>
                       sicians</orig>
                       <reg>physicians</reg>
                       </choice>
                       there who have tried to bleed <add>him</add> and<lb/>
                       tried all that could be tried for his<lb/>
                       recovery - And in short he would not go<lb/>
                       and he was right - And there is an<lb/>
                       end of that old friend - that ambitious, affectionate<lb/>
                       man -<lb/>
                   
                   <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-07-12_page02.jpg"/> 
                       - And the world goes on - And<lb/>
                       the question is who comes next<lb/>
                       into his place - And so it must<lb/>
                       be - We must either <hi rend="underline">live</hi> or die<lb/>
                       - Happy I think to die at once &amp;<lb/>
                       with only half an hours suffering<lb/>
                       to self - much the happiest - But<lb/>
                       the shock to friends is great -<lb/> </p>
                    
                   <p>
                       But now for the living - We<lb/>
                       had a very pleasant journey here<lb/>
                       literally in no time - for time was<lb/>
                       annihilated by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriets</persName> reading<lb/>
                       some of an old <add>or new</add> book I know not wh<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> of<lb/>
                       <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BaniJ1"><choice> 
                       <orig>Bannims</orig>
                       <reg>Banims</reg>
                       </choice></persName> , An admirable description<lb/>
                       of a benevolent Cat<hi rend="superscript">c</hi> . Priest who robs <choice> 
                       <orig>him<lb/>
                       self</orig>
                       <reg>himself</reg>
                       </choice>
                       and his housekeeper of their<lb/>
                       blankets one night for a wretched family<lb/>
                       and is <hi rend="underline">told</hi> of to his supreme housekeeper<lb/>
                       by a spy of a <unclear>gosvon</unclear> who has been lurking<lb/>
                       in the kitchen chimney corner &amp; has been <choice> 
                       <orig>direct<lb/>
                       ly</orig>
                       <reg>directly</reg>
                       </choice>
                       to housekeeper who is out unknownst at<lb/>
                       her tea drinking &amp; had left him locked in to <unclear>watch</unclear><lb/>
                       - The final battle between priest &amp; his<lb/>
                       housekeeper is admirable &amp; I wish that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName><lb/>
                       and you <add>&amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Lucy</persName></add> could see it<lb/> </p>
                    
                   <p>
                       But you are thinking of my teeth - All<lb/>
                       that were to be pulled out viz two are<lb/>
                       out and gave me very little pain -<lb/>
                       <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BropX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> . Brophy</persName> , tell <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Lucy</persName> is a very different<lb/>
                       sort of person from what I had expected<lb/>
                       <del>both</del> in external appearance &amp; speech<lb/>
                       I had imagined that he was unkempt<lb/>
                       unwashed round shouldered slump of<lb/>
                       a thorough going, jocose, tender <unclear>brougeoneer</unclear><lb/>
                       but I saw before me a <unclear>jemmy</unclear> , slim, upright<lb/>
                       little well accoutred man with nice curled<lb/>
                       hair and face more Italian <add>&amp;</add> penetrating than<lb/>
                       broad Irish - and except - "Dear!" and<lb/>
                       theres a <hi rend="underline">deer</hi> " - And wash your mouth again<lb/>
                       again now like a deer. - " There was none<lb/>
                       of the persuasive darling wheedling which<lb/>
                       I expected - I asked for but have not<lb/>
                   
                   <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-07-12_page03.jpg"/>
                       yet seen the brother - nor the dog <note>61</note><lb/>
                       - but will certainly see both this <choice> 
                       <orig>morn<lb/>
                       ing</orig>
                       <reg>morning</reg>
                       </choice>
                       - We are to be with him by 10 o clock<lb/>
                       - It is now 1/2 past 8) - He has taken a<lb/>
                       mould of the upper jaw but cannot of<lb/>
                       the lower till the gums harden where<lb/>
                       the teeth were - He says he can make<lb/>
                       as good a job for me as he has done for<lb/>
                       <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Lucy</persName> - I gave him great pleasure by<lb/>
                       telling him how well he has succeeded<lb/>
                       for her and how very comfortable she<lb/>
                       has been and how thankful she is to him<lb/> </p>
                    
                   <p>
                       <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeH1">Harriet</persName> has told you all about<lb/>
                       <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxM1" cert="high">Mary Anne's</persName> teeth - Happy creatures<lb/>
                       those two girls are - enjoying everything<lb/>
                       so much - <del></del> We go back to dear <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Trim</placeName><lb/>
                       today - 12 o clock - set out -<lb/> </p>
                    
                   <p>
                       Your packet has this instant <choice> 
                       <orig>ar-<lb/>
                       rived.</orig>
                       <reg>arrived</reg>
                       </choice>
                       I am very glad you approve<lb/>
                       of the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RuxtM1">Margaret Ruxton</persName> scheme - <del>And</del><lb/>
                       But as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> desires I will not<lb/>
                       decide in a hurry -<lb/> </p>
                    
                   <p>
                       Thank you for sending the <choice> 
                       <orig>dress-<lb/>
                       ing</orig>
                       <reg>dressing</reg>
                       </choice>
                       gown - I begin to believe that<lb/>
                       the thin one is my own after all<lb/>
                       <del></del> I suppose you are now in<lb/>
                       the midst of the greatest to wherry=<lb/>
                       go nimble about the packing up<lb/>
                       and the new cook and the <choice> 
                       <orig>house<lb/>
                       maid</orig>
                       <reg>housemaid</reg>
                       </choice>
                       who has not arrived &amp; all<lb/>
                       all upon your shoulders!<lb/> </p>
                    
                   <closer> 
                       God help you &amp; God bless you. I<lb/>
                       must go to breakfast and am<lb/>
                       in all circumstances, even before <choice> 
                       <orig>break<lb/>
                       fast</orig>
                       <reg>breakfast</reg>
                       </choice>
                       ever affectionately, your old <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria E</persName><lb/>  </closer>
                   
                   <postscript>
                       <p>
                       Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PakeX3" cert="high">Pakenham</persName> my love to him<lb/> </p>
                   <p>
                       I return here on Monday - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxC4">Charles</persName><lb/>
                   
                   <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-07-12_page04.jpg"/>
                       goes tomorrow - I dont know<lb/>
                       where<lb/> </p>
                       
                   <p> 
                       But ultimately or penultimately<lb/>
                       he goes to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Wiesbaden_DE">Wiesbaden</placeName> - too near<lb/>
                       <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mainz_DE">Mayence</placeName> where the <del></del> banished<lb/>
                       Foxs are - He says that if he<lb/>
                       went another way he should<lb/>
                       fall into the litter of the other Foxes<lb/>
                       a little worse - He looks sadly<lb/>
                       Dear good creature<lb/> </p>
                   
                   <p>
                       I hope <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1" cert="high">Francis</persName> will<lb/>
                       be satisfied with<lb/>
                       <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoffM1">Mary Moffatts</persName><lb/>
                       proposal - I<lb/>
                       will see her brother<lb/>
                       at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Trim_IE">Trim</placeName> &amp; get<lb/>
                       him to sign an<lb/>
                       agreement that<lb/>
                       I will draw up<lb/>
                       for swearing the<lb/>
                       £5p<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> ann<hi rend="superscript">m</hi> rent<lb/>
                       &amp; I will send it<lb/>
                       in to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF1" cert="high"><choice><orig>FBE</orig><reg>Francis Beaufort Edgeworth</reg></choice></persName>and then<lb/>
                       she may be let in<lb/>
                       to the house I think<lb/>
                       But not till then<lb/>
                       - And so much the<lb/>
                       better for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GahaX1">Gahan</persName> -<lb/>
                       He will not go into<lb/>
                       the newly plastered<lb/>
                       till quite dry - <lb/></p>
                </postscript>
                  
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
    </text>
